{{Infobox scientist | name = Bridget Terry Long | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = July 18, 1973 | birth_place = Baltimore, MA | spouse = Carl Long | children = 2 | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | citizenship = USA | nationality = USA | alma_mater = [[Princeton University]], [[Harvard University]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Caroline M. Hoxby]], [[Lawrence F. Katz]], and [[Claudia Goldin]] | doctoral_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | influenced = | signature = | website = http://www.bridgetterrylong.com | footnotes = | field = Economics | work_institutions = [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] | prizes = | religion = }}
'''Bridget Terry Long''' is the 12th Dean of the Harvard Graduate School of Education and the Saris Professor of Education and Economics.<ref>{{cite web||title=Bridget Terry Long to lead Ed School|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/05/bridget-terry-long-named-dean-of-harvard-ed-school/|website=harvard.edu|publisher=harvard.edu|accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref> She is also a [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] Faculty Research Associate,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.har.com/2017-calderwood-lecture-bridget-terry-long/event_E0-001-100590546-1|title=2017 Calderwood Lecture: Bridget Terry Long 02481 - HAR.com|website=Homes And Rentals - HAR.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref> and the former chair of the [[National Board of Education Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.payscale.com/college-roi/is-college-worth-it|title=Is College Worth It? Yes, But Not Always {{!}} PayScale|website=www.payscale.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref>
Her research focuses on the economics of education, particularly the transition from high school to college.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Bridget-Terry-Long/19221|title=Bridget Terry Long|date=2005-07-15|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref> Her work examines the factors that influence students' choices, the impact of financial aid programs, and the role of various factors in affecting student outcomes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/about-aea/committees/csmgep/profiles/bridget-terry-long|title=CSMGEP Profiles: Bridget Terry Long, Harvard University; Honing In on the Economics of Higher Education|website=www.aeaweb.org|language=en|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aera100.net/bridget-terry-long.html|title=Bridget Terry Long|website=www.aera100.net|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aera.net/Newsroom/News-Releases-and-Statements/Leading-Researcher-Bridget-Terry-Long-to-Address-College-Student-Access-and-Success-at-Los-Angeles-Event-on-Jan-11|title=Leading Researcher Bridget Terry Long to Address College Student Access and Success at Los Angeles Event on Jan. 11|website=www.aera.net|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref>
