{{Infobox website | name = securly:// | logo = S Logo 250.png | logo_size = 200px | url = {{URL|http://www.securly.com}} | type = [[Web filtering for schools]] | owner = [[Vinay Mahadik, Bharath Madhusudan]] | launch date = 2012 }}
'''Securly''' is a [[Silicon Valley]] based student safety company that provides software to K-12 schools and districts. Products include "Filter", a web filter that is fully custom for schools, "Auditor", an email filter for [[G Suite]], and "Tipline", an anonymous hotline for bullying to be used by students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.securly.com/|title=Securly - The Student Safety Company|last=|first=|date=|website=Securly|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> Securly is a venture-backed<ref name=UPenn-Wharton>[http://vip.wharton.upenn.edu/default.aspx "Wharton Venture Initiation Program"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908083048/http://vip.wharton.upenn.edu/default.aspx |date=2013-09-08 }}, [http://vip.wharton.upenn.edu/ http://vip.wharton.upenn.edu], 2011</ref> K-12 service provider based in Silicon Valley and was founded in 2012 by former [[McAfee]] network engineers Vinay Mahadlk<ref name=Wharton-magazine>[http://whartonmagazine.com/blogs/eager-for-entrepreneurship-at-wharton/ "Eager for Entrepreneurship at Wharton"], [http://whartonmagazine.com/ Wharton Magazine], 5 February 2013</ref> and Bharath Madhusudan.<ref name="securly1">{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/company/securly?trk=top_nav_home |title=LinkedIn: About Securly |publisher=LinkedIn|year=2012}}</ref>
Securly is said to use [[emotional learning]], [[natural language processing]] and other machine learning techniques, to study the differences between, when a kid is involved in acceptable research activities, versus engaging oneself in harmful and unacceptable behavior.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/10/20/securly-raises-4-million-to-put-guard-rails-on-the-internet-for-k-12-students/|title=Securly raises $4 million to put guard rails on the internet for K-12 students|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-10-09|language=en}}</ref>
Though Securly will charge for Filter on devices like the [[iPad]], [[MacBook]], and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] tablet, the [[Chromebook]] [[Chrome Web Store|Web Store Extension]] is free for G Suite Customers.
{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage=[[File:BharathDemoDay.jpeg|210px]]Securly Co-founder Bharath Madhusudan | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4DR4MYN4P_0 Securly at the Imagine K12 Demo Day] }}
==Philosophy== [[Content-control software|Web filters]] are commonly used for the purpose of preventing individuals from accessing websites. Securly, which serves only K-12 schools, employs a philosophy of using web filtering as a means of providing schools with data on how students are using their 1:1 devices in a positive manner.<ref name=AS>[http://anotherschwab.com/2015/02/07/the-power-of-positive-web-filtering/ "The Power of Positive Web Filtering"], [http://anotherschwab.com/ http://anotherschwab.com], 2015</ref>
==Recognition== In October 2014, Securly was one of the first K-12 Service Providers to sign the Student Privacy Pledge co-created by the [[Future of Privacy Forum]] and the [[Software and Information Industry Association]]. On January 12, 2015, Securly and 74 other companies, including [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and [[Microsoft]], were given recognition by President [[Barack Obama]] and the [[White House]] for their efforts to safeguard student data and privacy.<ref name="White House Office of the Press Secretary">[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/01/12/fact-sheet-safeguarding-american-consumers-families "FACT SHEET: Safeguarding American Consumers & Families"], [http://www.whitehouse.gov/ http://www.whitehouse.gov], 2015</ref>
In February 2015, Securly was reviewed by the popular educator website The Ed Tech Roundup and received a 5-star rating for its school product.<ref name="Ed Tech Roundup">[http://www.edtechroundup.org/reviews/securly-manage-screen-time-any-device-anywhere "Securly: Manage Screen Time - Any Device, Anywhere"], [http://www.edtechroundup.org/ http://www.edtechroundup.org], 2015</ref>
== Feedback == Securly gets a lot of negativity due to its constant blocking of safe sites. Checking the Chrome Web Store [https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/securly-for-chromebooks/iheobagjkfklnlikgihanlhcddjoihkg reviews] on Securly, you will find one star ratings, almost all from students, who are saying that it goes overboard with what sites it blocks.
